    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Reducing Hospital Error</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Irwin Mortman letter on pitfalls of accepting '99 percent' perfection by hospitals (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Ambitious Effort to Cut Mistakes in U.S. Hospitals'' (front page, Dec. 26): One needs the proper perspective when trying to improve quality. Most of us would think 99 percent perfection would be adequate, and that 99.9 percent would be even better.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Ambitious Effort to Cut Mistakes in U.S. Hospitals'' (front page, Dec. 26): One needs the proper perspective when trying to improve quality. Most of us would think 99 percent perfection would be adequate, and that 99.9 percent would be even better.</p>
        <p>But according to an article in INC magazine, 99.9 percent quality means one hour of unsafe drinking water every month; two unsafe landings a day at O'Hare Airport, and 16,000 pieces of mail lost by the Post Office every hour.</p>
        <p>It also means 20,000 incorrect drug prescriptions a year; 500 incorrect surgical operations a week; 50 newborn babies dropped at birth every day; 22,000 checks deducted from the wrong bank account every hour, and 32,000 missed heartbeats a person every year.</p>
        <p>IRWIN MORTMAN  Cincinnati, Dec. 27, 1999</p>
      </block>
